1. nec . . . nec . . . nec: the variety in the MSS. [cf. ἐξ 3, 51] seems to indicate a tendency to substitute neque for nec, especially before a vowel. Land- graf, in RH. n. 408, says that on account of such variety, no sure conclusions as to the use of nec before a vowel can be arrived at. ‘Caesar objected to nec before a vowel, and so formed inopinans, the author of the Alexandrian war uses neque opinans, Cicero employs nec opinans.' W olfflin remarks a tendency to use a second nec before a vowel, if preceded by nec before a consonant, e. g. nec plumbum nec aurum. Here nec before imperante seems preferred in anticipation of nec . . . nec which follow.

Cf. de Inv. i. 103 a seras hominibus et a bar- baris genttbus et immanibus bestiis. It also is contrary to the sense. Cicero's point is that the law of sels defence is common to animals as well as to man. Feris beluis would confine this statement to ‘ savage animals.' These, however, would naturally defend themselves: a stronger assertion is that gentler ereatures will do so, e. g. the stag as well as the lion or tiger.
